<br>
Why should these kings, lords, dukes be any different than dictators today? We have seen many dictators using their politics, and often a polictical faction, to keep their population in line. China, Chile, Germany and Italy during ww2 and so on.<br>
<br>
Its more likely that human nature abuse the religion than the religion dictates human nature. The pattern of wars havnt changed since religion lost it influence of the state. On the contrary the world have never seen as many wars as we experience now. Powerstruggles and economy are more likely reasons for a war, even the old wars with religious motives.<br>
<br>
Well, back to the religious person. Religious is a question of belief. If you belive in god, karma or whatever thats enough for that person and might give him/her a better life? So whats wrong with this? Nothing. To be honest I often envy a person that can use religion to overcome obstacles in life, bring him joy, love, meaning, understanding, friends, tolerance. Maybe the person wont need to play Everquest to fill his day?<br>
<br>
I myself was 100% devoted to scientific explanations of everything like most people today but after studying filosophi I began to question the values I was beliving in. I used to feel people beliving was 'lesser' people in some ways cause couldnt they see that their beliefs were wrong? I mean, science could explain so much that religion couldnt really support. I should be easy to prove to a christian that God didnt create the universe but Big Bang did. (Or whatever theori you lean towards.)<br>
<br>
But it dosnt matter what I tell them. I can come with all my fancy words and calculations and it wasnt important to them cause they had their faith, they belived in God. I realised that they laughed at me and now, even though I'm not religious and still belive in science, I laugh with them when someone tries to convince them that God dosnt exist because it dosnt matter to them. <br>
<br>
<br>
